Ok, it works this way:

```
webContents.executeJavascript(`
  ipc = require('ipc');
  Notification = function(title, options) {
    ipc.send('notify', {title: title, options: options});
  }
  Notification.permission = 'granted'
`
```

This way I can listen in main thread on `notify` messages and do whatever I want with them.

I tried @hleumas idea and it worked well for me. So I made [electron-notification-shim](https://github.com/seriema/electron-notification-shim) in case someone else wants to use it. You can install it from [npm](https://www.npmjs.com/package/electron-notification-shim).

```
// Require and run in rendering process.
// Put it in a `if(process.platform === 'win32')` if you only want it for Windows.
require('electron-notification-shim')();
```

```
// Get events in main process.
ipc.on('notification-shim', (e, msg) => { ... });
```

From there you can pop up toasters with @s-a's [electron-toaster](https://github.com/s-a/electron-toaster), or [node-notifier](https://github.com/mikaelbr/node-notifier) which worked out of the box for me (not sure what @paulcbetts meant). The event also worked well for adding badges to the app icon, and counting missed notifications in the rendering view by using `e.returnValue =` or `e.sender.send()` from the main process. It's been so useful I'm wondering if `electron` triggering a `notification` event would be the way forward?

